00:10:58,483 --> 00:11:01,486
My nerves and my skin were getting habituated to the sensation of the sun.

257
00:11:01,526 --> 00:11:05,830
And habituation is the reduction in sensitivity when something happens over and over and over again.

258
00:11:07,311 --> 00:11:10,254
Now you might think this is bad as in the case of a sunburn,

259
00:11:10,454 --> 00:11:13,997
but it's actually extremely important as I found out later when my sunburn started to heal

260
00:11:14,337 --> 00:11:19,061
and it itched madly and I couldn't sleep and I couldn't have a conversation

261
00:11:19,141 --> 00:11:22,644
and I couldn't even really think straight because I couldn't do anything but feel my skin.

262
00:11:22,985 --> 00:11:25,647
And if you didn't have habituation, you would feel like that all the time.

263
00:11:26,824 --> 00:11:28,886
Habituation is also a really crucial learning tool.

264
00:11:28,906 --> 00:11:31,307
So when you see something in a game over and over and over,

265
00:11:31,367 --> 00:11:32,388
you get habituated to it.

266
00:11:33,329 --> 00:11:34,630
You stop noticing it, and you start

267
00:11:34,690 --> 00:11:37,112
noticing the differences between the experiences that

268
00:11:37,152 --> 00:11:39,413
allow you to analyze them and come up

269
00:11:39,433 --> 00:11:40,314
with different strategies.

270
00:11:41,335 --> 00:11:43,136
But it's also the designer's mortal enemy.

271
00:11:43,656 --> 00:11:44,957
Habituation makes you bored.

272
00:11:45,458 --> 00:11:48,039
So what you should be going for in a fun experience

273
00:11:48,220 --> 00:11:51,882
is predictable enough that you can habituate to it somewhat

274
00:11:51,982 --> 00:11:53,984
and learn it, but not so predictable, not

275
00:11:54,044 --> 00:11:55,165
so habituatable.

276
00:11:56,030 --> 00:11:57,051
that you get bored.

277
00:11:58,131 --> 00:11:59,412
And finally, it needs to be reliable.

278
00:12:00,113 --> 00:12:03,855
It needs to be fun every time for as many people as possible,

279
00:12:03,915 --> 00:12:04,296
ideally.

280
00:12:04,736 --> 00:12:07,658
And it turns out these kind of reliable activities

281
00:12:07,678 --> 00:12:09,239
are extraordinarily rare.

282
00:12:09,799 --> 00:12:11,961
And you probably participated in most of them

283
00:12:11,981 --> 00:12:13,062
by the time you were five or six.

284
00:12:14,403 --> 00:12:15,163
What do I mean by that?

285
00:12:15,503 --> 00:12:18,085
You didn't throw a grenade before you were six,

286
00:12:18,365 --> 00:12:21,447
hopefully, unless you're breaking the ESRB.

287
00:12:24,009 --> 00:12:24,610
So grenades are.

288
00:12:25,625 --> 00:12:30,266
staple of Halo gameplay. But really, when you look at the experience of throwing a grenade,

289
00:12:31,086 --> 00:12:37,828
it's really close to Peggle, which finds its roots in games like Arkanoid. I mean, how

290
00:12:37,868 --> 00:12:40,689
many of you are itching for that ball to go right up that crack and then bounce off the

291
00:12:40,709 --> 00:12:46,051
ground? If you don't know what Arkanoid is, maybe Angry Birds is a better reference for

292
00:12:46,071 --> 00:12:50,732
throwing grenades. Which goes back to, like, in physical activities, like pool, you know,

293
00:12:51,952 --> 00:12:55,273
what angle do I have to hit the bumper at in order for, to make the pocket?

294
00:12:56,497 --> 00:12:58,999
Which, even, you know, even when you were a little child,

295
00:12:59,559 --> 00:13:00,900
throwing stuff in a waste paper basket.

296
00:13:01,201 --> 00:13:03,422
It's all that same kind of fundamental activity

297
00:13:03,442 --> 00:13:04,323
that you could just do forever.

298
00:13:05,324 --> 00:13:06,304
So maybe you're not convinced.

299
00:13:07,065 --> 00:13:07,726
What about melee?

300
00:13:09,026 --> 00:13:10,187
It's another Halo staple.

301
00:13:10,888 --> 00:13:11,909
Really important part of the game.

302
00:13:12,429 --> 00:13:13,009
Never gets old.

303
00:13:13,910 --> 00:13:15,551
Just like it never got old in Final Fight.

304
00:13:17,333 --> 00:13:21,076
Just like it convinced you to hit all those stupid Flash banner ads.

305
00:13:22,437 --> 00:13:24,838
I couldn't, I couldn't find the Punch-a-Monkey.

306
00:13:25,420 --> 00:13:28,122
There is no actual copy of that on the internet anymore.

307
00:13:29,883 --> 00:13:32,784
Which, when you think about it, is really just a callback

308
00:13:33,164 --> 00:13:34,345
to Whack-A-Mole.

309
00:13:34,925 --> 00:13:37,347
And Whack-A-Mole is just a machine playing sort

310
00:13:37,367 --> 00:13:38,787
of a violent version of peekaboo.

311
00:13:39,408 --> 00:13:41,569
This is my son, and he's super cute.

312
00:13:42,109 --> 00:13:43,710
So I wanted to use him in my presentation.

313
00:13:45,211 --> 00:13:45,911
How about the Warthog?

314
00:13:47,712 --> 00:13:51,734
The Warthog, way slidier than any actual vehicle,

315
00:13:52,575 --> 00:13:53,475
just like in Mario Kart.

316
00:13:53,936 --> 00:13:57,497
which is very similar to skiing, which is just like sliding around in your socks.

317
00:13:58,337 --> 00:14:00,698
Or in her socks, preferably.

318
00:14:02,258 --> 00:14:03,339
So why are these things fun?

319
00:14:03,599 --> 00:14:07,660
There's a book called The Brain That Changes Itself, and it talks about people who have

320
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:20,004
suffered mostly brain injuries or birth defects that use practice and rote skills to sort

321
00:14:20,024 --> 00:14:23,145
of regenerate their brain tissue.

322
00:14:23,794 --> 00:14:30,676
And it says that a trained or stimulated neuron develops 25% more branches, increases its size,

323
00:14:30,996 --> 00:14:33,757
and it gets a lot more blood supply going through it.

324
00:14:34,337 --> 00:14:39,638
And so my theory is that just like physical exercise is fun just for the sake of exercise,

325
00:14:39,958 --> 00:14:41,559
mental exercise is fun in the same way.

326
00:14:42,599 --> 00:14:47,581
So if you look at dodging, which is something that you did when you were a child,

327
00:14:48,901 --> 00:14:50,441
there's lots and lots of things that you're doing.

328
00:14:50,481 --> 00:14:50,881
You are...

329
00:14:52,297 --> 00:14:53,938
You're detecting movement in your peripheral vision,

330
00:14:54,538 --> 00:14:57,379
and you are tracking objects as they move across the space,

331
00:14:59,240 --> 00:15:02,381
which translates really well into 2D in a game like Commando,

332
00:15:02,421 --> 00:15:02,881
for instance.

333
00:15:03,601 --> 00:15:05,562
But it's even better in 3D, where

334
00:15:05,602 --> 00:15:08,643
you're trying to take the non-linear change in size

335
00:15:08,743 --> 00:15:10,764
of a projectile as it comes toward you and determine

336
00:15:11,184 --> 00:15:12,425
when it's going to intersect with you

337
00:15:13,505 --> 00:15:17,206
and predict its trajectory, or determine the closest point

338
00:15:17,246 --> 00:15:18,867
that it's going to reach so you know exactly

339
00:15:18,907 --> 00:15:19,907
how far you have to dodge.

340
00:15:20,848 --> 00:15:20,948
So.

341
00:15:21,798 --> 00:15:24,598
Just a quick tangent, the conventional wisdom is that 3D sucks.

342
00:15:25,219 --> 00:15:29,379
And maybe the technology isn't there yet, but eventually games are going to be in 3D

343
00:15:29,459 --> 00:15:32,800
and they're going to be way more fun because they're going to tap more directly into those

344
00:15:33,220 --> 00:15:33,760
brain circuits.

345
00:15:36,361 --> 00:15:36,601
OK.

346
00:15:39,001 --> 00:15:42,742
Games, other than Halo, are fun for this reason.

347
00:15:42,822 --> 00:15:46,763
So your brain is really good at pattern matching and actually has, like, physical hardware

348
00:15:46,783 --> 00:15:47,103
for that.

349
00:15:47,223 --> 00:15:49,063
So that explains things like Tetris.

350
00:15:50,803 --> 00:15:54,084
Predicting complex systems with an almost intuition level

351
00:15:54,104 --> 00:15:55,124
is common.

352
00:15:56,465 --> 00:15:59,065
You have special circuits for determining a rate of change,

353
00:15:59,105 --> 00:16:00,946
and especially comparing one rate of change to another.

354
00:16:01,026 --> 00:16:03,867
So if you've ever tried to see if your healer's mana was

355
00:16:03,907 --> 00:16:06,648
going to last longer than a boss's life in WoW,

356
00:16:06,688 --> 00:16:07,348
that's what you're doing.

357
00:16:08,328 --> 00:16:10,329
Path planning is pretty obvious in a game like Pac-Man,

358
00:16:10,349 --> 00:16:12,910
but it's also when you're trying to complete three or four

359
00:16:12,950 --> 00:16:15,090
quests in an area, you're trying to do it most efficiently.

360
00:16:16,487 --> 00:16:19,788
Your plasticity is sort of how you make new connections

361
00:16:19,828 --> 00:16:20,728
that you never had before.

362
00:16:20,748 --> 00:16:23,109
I think Portal probably stretched everybody's brains

363
00:16:23,129 --> 00:16:23,490
a little bit.

364
00:16:24,150 --> 00:16:27,891
And finally, another thing that you're hardwired for

365
00:16:28,171 --> 00:16:30,813
is to have a theory of mind to try

366
00:16:30,833 --> 00:16:32,493
to get inside somebody else's head, which

367
00:16:32,573 --> 00:16:34,874
is very useful in something like Street Fighter

368
00:16:34,894 --> 00:16:35,935
or even a slow game like chess.

369
00:16:36,575 --> 00:16:37,796
So back to reality.

370
00:16:37,856 --> 00:16:38,036
OK.

371
00:16:38,496 --> 00:16:40,177
So we need something that's reactive, repeatable,

372
00:16:40,217 --> 00:16:43,218
reliable, that exercises your dodging circuits.

373
00:16:43,574 --> 00:16:46,195
And so we rewrote the plasma rifle paper design

374
00:16:46,275 --> 00:16:49,236
to say it's a high rate of fire gun that

375
00:16:49,256 --> 00:16:50,496
shoots plasma bullets that travel

376
00:16:50,516 --> 00:16:51,736
at a fast but dodgeable speed.

377
00:16:57,438 --> 00:17:00,199
So that mechanic works itself out in this way.

378
00:17:00,659 --> 00:17:01,579
We don't want it to be too fast.

379
00:17:01,599 --> 00:17:02,920
We want to give you enough time to dodge.

380
00:17:03,660 --> 00:17:04,920
And also we want it to be slow enough

381
00:17:04,940 --> 00:17:07,801
that it's a continuous motion, because we're actually just

382
00:17:07,821 --> 00:17:09,242
throwing up 30 still frames a second.

383
00:17:12,045 --> 00:17:13,986
If you can't connect those in your brain

384
00:17:14,026 --> 00:17:17,227
into a single, believable, real object,

385
00:17:17,567 --> 00:17:20,468
then you can't engage those dodging circuits.

386
00:17:20,928 --> 00:17:23,468
And we gave it a really visible contrail,

387
00:17:24,849 --> 00:17:26,889
which was especially useful in the PAL version,

388
00:17:26,989 --> 00:17:28,770
actually, where it's harder to dodge because you're

389
00:17:28,790 --> 00:17:29,730
getting fewer updates.

390
00:17:30,830 --> 00:17:31,931
But we didn't want it to be too slow.

391
00:17:32,011 --> 00:17:34,291
I mean, it's sort of comical if the bullets are just

392
00:17:34,331 --> 00:17:34,911
hanging in air.

393
00:17:35,312 --> 00:17:36,772
And we still want you to experience

394
00:17:36,792 --> 00:17:37,532
all those near misses.

395
00:17:41,313 --> 00:17:43,773
So that just brings me to a sort of a fundamental definition

396
00:17:43,793 --> 00:17:47,014
of game mechanics, where you divide the potential gameplay

397
00:17:47,034 --> 00:17:49,315
into two parts, actions that are permitted

398
00:17:49,355 --> 00:17:50,355
and actions that aren't permitted.

399
00:17:51,335 --> 00:17:53,856
So Mario cannot jump over the flag.

400
00:17:54,256 --> 00:17:55,256
Mario cannot run left.

401
00:17:55,416 --> 00:17:57,017
There are just things that Mario cannot do.

402
00:17:57,977 --> 00:18:00,177
This is good, because it allows us to constrain the game.

403
00:18:01,058 --> 00:18:04,078
But the problem is that one mechanic isn't a game.

404
00:18:04,298 --> 00:18:05,819
It's not even really interactive.

405
00:18:06,339 --> 00:18:08,399
If you only have one constraint, then you're

406
00:18:08,419 --> 00:18:09,420
not making any choices.

407
00:18:10,242 --> 00:18:14,704
I recently made my first Flash game, and it's Pac-Man in a line.

408
00:18:15,304 --> 00:18:20,566
Basically there's no ghosts, there's no maze, you just eat all the dots, and it's boring.

409
00:18:22,447 --> 00:18:28,149
So if we look at a Halo mechanic, let's say that there's a mechanic where your hand-held

410
00:18:28,189 --> 00:18:30,270
weapon, it beats distant enemies, right?

411
00:18:30,430 --> 00:18:35,352
And so if they are distant, then you win, if they're not distant, then you lose.

412
00:18:38,600 --> 00:18:46,945
sort of a contemporary design theory is that, excuse me, that you should layer new mechanics

413
00:18:47,225 --> 00:18:51,748
on top of this one. And if you layer off enough mechanics, then you're going to make a game.

414
00:18:51,768 --> 00:18:56,351
And if your game isn't fun, then you should layer on more mechanics. But I really think

415
00:18:56,431 --> 00:19:01,514
all that does is give you a larger number of choices that you aren't making. So what

416
00:19:01,534 --> 00:19:05,336
I suggest is that you want to have

417
00:19:05,712 --> 00:19:08,454
mechanics that support each other, sort of like a tripod.

418
00:19:08,554 --> 00:19:09,535
They're leaning against each other.

419
00:19:10,035 --> 00:19:12,257
And all the area inside is the gameplay.

420
00:19:12,337 --> 00:19:15,199
And so a sandbox game has a huge area.

421
00:19:15,419 --> 00:19:17,821
And maybe a more linear game has a much smaller area.

422
00:19:17,841 --> 00:19:21,724
But at least there's lots of different possible places

423
00:19:21,764 --> 00:19:23,125
that the player could be at any given time.

424
00:19:24,085 --> 00:19:26,227
So that means that the projectile mechanics also

425
00:19:26,267 --> 00:19:27,868
need to be supported by AI mechanics.

426
00:19:28,428 --> 00:19:29,509
So they lead to your peers.

427
00:19:29,709 --> 00:19:31,050
And we had them fight from the open

428
00:19:31,431 --> 00:19:32,932
so that you could see them fighting from the open

429
00:19:32,972 --> 00:19:33,412
and dodging.

430
00:19:33,452 --> 00:19:34,553
And that would teach you to dodge.

431
00:19:35,409 --> 00:19:37,090
We also made them shoot directly at the player,

432
00:19:37,490 --> 00:19:38,951
because it's a lot easier to dodge something that's

433
00:19:38,991 --> 00:19:40,451
coming straight at you, rather than

434
00:19:40,471 --> 00:19:42,292
trying to figure out which direction you're

435
00:19:42,312 --> 00:19:43,012
going to need to dodge.

436
00:19:43,913 --> 00:19:45,193
We gave them a little bit of small error,

437
00:19:45,213 --> 00:19:47,294
so it wasn't quite as predictable.

438
00:19:48,355 --> 00:19:51,736
And they also shoot in bursts, so sort of like a fan pattern.

439
00:19:51,756 --> 00:19:53,237
Doom, doom, doom, doom, doom.

440
00:19:53,277 --> 00:19:54,177
They kind of swing it across.

441
00:19:55,818 --> 00:19:57,239
But they don't track the player during a burst.

442
00:19:57,299 --> 00:19:58,639
So if you start dodging a burst, you're

443
00:19:58,659 --> 00:19:59,720
going to be able to dodge the rest of it.

444
00:20:01,802 --> 00:20:03,502
The player mechanics also needed to support this.

445
00:20:03,582 --> 00:20:07,003
So instead of having the blazingly fast super soldier,

446
00:20:07,323 --> 00:20:10,144
we had an agonizingly slow super soldier,

447
00:20:10,704 --> 00:20:12,464
mostly relying on the acceleration

448
00:20:12,964 --> 00:20:14,385
of going left to right.

449
00:20:14,765 --> 00:20:16,345
You have to anticipate what you're going to dodge.

450
00:20:16,365 --> 00:20:18,626
You can't just immediately move out of the way

451
00:20:19,086 --> 00:20:21,367
as if you were a Ferrari.

452
00:20:22,687 --> 00:20:25,167
And we also had a narrow field of view,

453
00:20:25,207 --> 00:20:29,248
which is not a common thing at the time.

454
00:20:29,589 --> 00:20:31,469
PC games had the crazy fish eye.

455
00:20:32,155 --> 00:20:37,918
views and the reason is it makes objects that are distant in the middle of the screen feel

456
00:20:37,958 --> 00:20:42,840
like they're much closer and larger and that allows you to track projectiles a lot better

457
00:20:42,880 --> 00:20:45,741
because instead of being really, really, really small and then all of a sudden being huge

458
00:20:45,761 --> 00:20:49,762
and in your face, they're actually increasing as they would in the real world via inverse

459
00:20:49,782 --> 00:20:50,243
square law.

460
00:20:52,083 --> 00:20:55,325
We gave the player shields which recharge after a short time.

461
00:20:56,005 --> 00:20:58,486
So that means if you're dodging and you get a couple shots, it's not that risky.

462
00:20:58,983 --> 00:21:02,585
And so we actually increased the amount of damage that a plasma rifle will do against

463
00:21:02,765 --> 00:21:03,085
shields.

464
00:21:03,446 --> 00:21:08,408
But at the same time we gave you body health that doesn't recharge, so we wanted to preserve

465
00:21:08,428 --> 00:21:12,490
your life by making you do a little bit less damage to body.

466
00:21:14,731 --> 00:21:16,832
When it comes to difficulty in Halo 1, it's pretty straightforward.

467
00:21:16,892 --> 00:21:20,253
We had these red elites and they were like tougher versions of the blue elites.

468
00:21:20,293 --> 00:21:23,154
They shot more bursts, they shot longer bursts, so they're a little bit harder.

469
00:21:24,055 --> 00:21:27,717
And we had a global weapon damage scale, so on Legendary.

470
00:21:28,369 --> 00:21:30,710
everything did about twice as much damage to the player.

471
00:21:33,071 --> 00:21:35,051
So mechanics are universal.

472
00:21:35,211 --> 00:21:40,753
If the game designer writes down plasma rifle bolts are dodgeable, then they are in abstract

473
00:21:40,793 --> 00:21:45,455
mechanic land, but they need to be calibrated to make them personal and effective in the

474
00:21:45,495 --> 00:21:45,915
real world.

475
00:21:46,735 --> 00:21:50,176
These are the actual numbers that create the experience that the mechanic is describing

476
00:21:50,697 --> 00:21:53,758
and make the plasma rifle dodgeable for a certain player.

477
00:21:54,018 --> 00:21:56,238
So in Halo, it was calibrated for me.

478
00:21:57,259 --> 00:21:58,059
Actually, I've said that before.

479
00:21:58,735 --> 00:22:00,296
Actually, it's not precisely true.

480
00:22:01,436 --> 00:22:06,180
So ask yourself, and hopefully you're not already asking this of yourself, why did you

481
00:22:06,220 --> 00:22:07,480
come to this talk today?

482
00:22:08,701 --> 00:22:09,442
Confabulation!

483
00:22:12,724 --> 00:22:16,986
The truth is that you can't recreate your subconscious mind in your conscious mind.

484
00:22:17,046 --> 00:22:20,529
It's like trying to emulate an Xbox on an Atari 2600.

485
00:22:20,569 --> 00:22:21,289
It just doesn't fit.

486
00:22:21,649 --> 00:22:25,912
And so what you have is an internal model, which you use to guess at your own motivations.

487
00:22:26,942 --> 00:22:29,143
Usually it's pretty accurate because you have a lot of experience with yourself.

488
00:22:29,823 --> 00:22:32,803
But what you should do is also build one of these internal models for the player.

489
00:22:34,144 --> 00:22:37,564
That way you can predict the player reactions and so when you're calibrating, you're calibrating

490
00:22:37,644 --> 00:22:41,805
for this little internal guy that you believe is what is representative of every player.

491
00:22:43,365 --> 00:22:46,386
So this is my job.

492
00:22:47,906 --> 00:22:51,567
It's also the series of steps that led to the calibration of the plasma rifle.

493
00:22:53,902 --> 00:22:56,324
The process for me usually goes like this.

494
00:22:56,765 --> 00:22:58,446
I make my best guess, which in this case was 10,

495
00:22:58,486 --> 00:22:59,988
because I had no idea.

496
00:23:00,548 --> 00:23:03,050
10 is world units per second, which

497
00:23:03,571 --> 00:23:07,114
is a unit of measurement that means absolutely nothing to you.

498
00:23:09,075 --> 00:23:10,577
And then I would try the extremes.

499
00:23:10,717 --> 00:23:12,478
So I would try 20, and I'm like, wow,

500
00:23:12,518 --> 00:23:13,900
that is almost instantaneous.

501
00:23:14,300 --> 00:23:16,902
Or 1, and I have to wait for the bullets to get to me,

502
00:23:16,962 --> 00:23:18,524
and sometimes I forget they're there and fall asleep,

503
00:23:18,544 --> 00:23:19,044
and then they hit me.

504
00:23:19,835 --> 00:23:24,276
Um, so then I narrowed in on the value, so I tried five, and that was better, but it

505
00:23:24,316 --> 00:23:29,177
was still way too easy to dodge, so I moved to 15, which, oh, that is too fast, and then

506
00:23:29,217 --> 00:23:34,838
I moved to 13, which is totally dodgeable, until I tried to pay attention to something

507
00:23:34,898 --> 00:23:38,718
else and shoot back, and then I'm getting hit again, so I turned it to 11, which felt

508
00:23:38,778 --> 00:23:42,779
really good, and then after a while it kind of felt too good, so then I bumped it up to 12.

509
00:23:44,319 --> 00:23:44,539
Twelve.

510
00:23:47,300 --> 00:23:48,860
So the, uh, experience.

511
00:23:49,690 --> 00:23:52,812
that your calibration gives you is something that you need to test and use your research,

512
00:23:52,912 --> 00:23:57,154
obviously. For us, we found that players could dodge the plasma bolts and that felt really

513
00:23:57,174 --> 00:24:02,456
good for them, but it had some unintended consequences in Halo 1. First, they were fighting

514
00:24:02,716 --> 00:24:07,918
out in the open, so they saw more of the enemy behaviors, which is good, but they also died

515
00:24:07,958 --> 00:24:12,720
without seeking cover because they wanted to only fight out from the open, which was

516
00:24:12,780 --> 00:24:15,562
not so good. And then it was also extremely broken.

517
00:24:16,823 --> 00:24:19,425
So basically, you can always dodge the plasma rifle

518
00:24:19,685 --> 00:24:20,726
in Halo.

519
00:24:21,166 --> 00:24:22,447
And this is why.

520
00:24:24,509 --> 00:24:26,771
If you aim directly at the player as an AI,

521
00:24:27,531 --> 00:24:29,093
and the player's moving, you're going to miss.

522
00:24:30,133 --> 00:24:32,015
So you could solve that by trying to lead.

523
00:24:32,675 --> 00:24:35,017
The problem is, if they zigzag at all,

524
00:24:35,317 --> 00:24:36,138
you miss by even more.

525
00:24:37,499 --> 00:24:40,121
If your projectile is dramatically slower

526
00:24:40,161 --> 00:24:42,943
than the player, then this is not a solvable problem.

527
00:24:44,028 --> 00:24:46,289
And basically, if you know that this is the case in Halo,

528
00:24:46,369 --> 00:24:48,510
you can break the game pretty badly

529
00:24:49,070 --> 00:24:50,891
on pretty much every difficulty level

530
00:24:50,951 --> 00:24:51,691
and in every encounter.

531
00:24:52,211 --> 00:24:52,671
So that's bad.

532
00:24:55,412 --> 00:24:56,252
When it comes to multiplayer,

533
00:24:57,773 --> 00:24:58,973
we had added movement stuns.

534
00:24:58,993 --> 00:25:00,954
So when you get shot by the plasma rifle,

535
00:25:02,114 --> 00:25:03,235
it makes it so you can't turn as fast

536
00:25:03,255 --> 00:25:04,515
and you can't move as fast.

537
00:25:05,055 --> 00:25:06,516
And that was to compensate for the fact

538
00:25:06,536 --> 00:25:08,256
that it just wasn't, you know,

539
00:25:08,276 --> 00:25:10,957
you couldn't use it at a good range

540
00:25:11,797 --> 00:25:13,518
because it was traveling so slowly.

541
00:25:14,508 --> 00:25:17,811
But an unintended consequence of that was that movement sound was really annoying.

542
00:25:18,371 --> 00:25:22,155
It works okay in Counter-Strike when you're gonna get shot three times and then die, but

543
00:25:22,175 --> 00:25:25,638
in our game when you could take a lot of hits, you would just have to sit there and take

544
00:25:25,658 --> 00:25:29,882
a lot of hits, which conflicted with the Halo flavor quite a bit.

545
00:25:30,443 --> 00:25:36,188
It was also horribly broken because you could use it on vehicles, which... whatever.

546
00:25:36,208 --> 00:25:37,990
It was a short development cycle, what can I say?

547
00:25:39,882 --> 00:25:44,125
Now when it comes to Legendary, this is kind of interesting because the Plasma Rifle, as

548
00:25:44,405 --> 00:25:46,047
all weapons, did twice as much damage.

549
00:25:46,267 --> 00:25:47,768
So that made Legendary very difficult.

550
00:25:50,250 --> 00:25:51,831
Had some unintended consequences.

551
00:25:51,891 --> 00:25:57,676
Basically the difficulty scale was stacking with the material scale I described earlier.

552
00:25:57,756 --> 00:26:01,839
So against shields it was actually doing almost four times as much damage, which meant that

553
00:26:01,899 --> 00:26:04,121
it was taking down your shields almost instantly.

554
00:26:07,464 --> 00:26:08,704
The way this was badly broken.

555
00:26:09,683 --> 00:26:13,704
was, so dodging was not actually any harder.

556
00:26:14,164 --> 00:26:18,245
So on normal, you could dodge back and forth,

557
00:26:18,305 --> 00:26:19,925
and every projectile would miss you.

558
00:26:20,225 --> 00:26:21,506
And if a couple hit you, that was fine.

559
00:26:21,526 --> 00:26:22,186
You just take cover.

560
00:26:22,586 --> 00:26:24,106
In legendary, you could dodge back and forth

561
00:26:24,346 --> 00:26:25,246
in the exact same way.

562
00:26:26,047 --> 00:26:28,667
The same number of bolts would hit you, and they would kill you.

563
00:26:28,887 --> 00:26:30,748
So we weren't actually making the game harder.

564
00:26:30,768 --> 00:26:32,648
We were just making it more punishing.

565
00:26:33,528 --> 00:26:36,389
But luckily, we got a chance to fix everything in Halo 2.

566
00:26:39,889 --> 00:26:41,169
So again, we're looking at the competition.

567
00:26:41,650 --> 00:26:43,730
Ghost Recon came about that time.

568
00:26:44,310 --> 00:26:45,951
And it was different than an Unreal

569
00:26:45,991 --> 00:26:47,331
and that had instant projectiles.

570
00:26:47,371 --> 00:26:48,892
It was really encouraging you to fight from cover.

571
00:26:49,532 --> 00:26:52,253
Rainbow Six came out and it also had instant projectiles

572
00:26:52,293 --> 00:26:53,053
and fighting from cover.

573
00:26:53,393 --> 00:26:55,153
And Counter-Strike, and S.W.A.T., and Medal of Honor,

574
00:26:55,173 --> 00:26:56,834
and Minerva, and Call of Duty, and Kill Switch.

575
00:26:57,474 --> 00:26:58,975
So basically we're seeing a trend here.

576
00:27:01,015 --> 00:27:02,736
People want instant projectiles and fighting from cover.

577
00:27:03,816 --> 00:27:04,716
We looked at our own community.

578
00:27:05,336 --> 00:27:07,837
And the Halo 1 pistol is.

579
00:27:09,291 --> 00:27:12,292
really unbalanced and really popular.

580
00:27:12,652 --> 00:27:14,332
And we think that's probably because, hey,

581
00:27:14,352 --> 00:27:15,193
it's an innocent projectile.

582
00:27:16,533 --> 00:27:18,914
Legendary is also, like I described before,

583
00:27:19,254 --> 00:27:21,434
completely unbalanced and very popular,

584
00:27:21,734 --> 00:27:24,135
which means that people enjoy the fighting from cover,

585
00:27:24,195 --> 00:27:25,675
even if it's excessively punishing.

586
00:27:27,276 --> 00:27:29,797
So we talked earlier about how fun requires participation.

587
00:27:29,917 --> 00:27:32,837
And what that means is that fun requires buy-in.

588
00:27:33,658 --> 00:27:35,638
Basically, people will play the game that they want to play,

589
00:27:36,318 --> 00:27:36,878
no matter what.

590
00:27:38,460 --> 00:27:43,262
I did the Halo 1 tutorial, and before giving you a weapon in the original version of the

591
00:27:43,282 --> 00:27:47,624
tutorial, I would throw you into combat, and the idea was, it would teach people to run

592
00:27:47,664 --> 00:27:47,884
away.

593
00:27:48,904 --> 00:27:53,967
What we tell people was, run up next to a guy and let them shoot you to death, because

594
00:27:54,027 --> 00:27:57,308
you can't figure out how to kill them because you can't, because you don't have a weapon

595
00:27:57,568 --> 00:27:57,708
yet.

596
00:27:58,048 --> 00:28:04,951
People will, they go with their expectation over any kind of hint text or recommendation

597
00:28:04,971 --> 00:28:05,332
that you can make.

598
00:28:07,470 --> 00:28:09,772
Again, the most important context tended to be in the game.

599
00:28:10,593 --> 00:28:16,017
The elites in Halo 2 were not the faceless enemy

600
00:28:16,037 --> 00:28:16,677
that they were in Halo 1.

601
00:28:16,797 --> 00:28:18,459
In fact, sometimes they were your allies.

602
00:28:18,679 --> 00:28:19,779
And at some points in the game, you

603
00:28:19,799 --> 00:28:21,040
were actually playing as an elite.

604
00:28:21,501 --> 00:28:24,403
And so they needed an instant projectile weapon

605
00:28:24,803 --> 00:28:25,584
in their arsenal.

606
00:28:26,805 --> 00:28:29,487
Also, in single player, we decided

607
00:28:29,507 --> 00:28:31,588
since dodging is not fixable, maybe we'll

608
00:28:31,608 --> 00:28:33,089
emphasize fighting from cover a little bit more.

609
00:28:34,370 --> 00:28:35,191
And in multiplayer.

610
00:28:35,688 --> 00:28:37,709
Since movement sign is just not fitting with the game,

611
00:28:38,629 --> 00:28:41,090
again, we want to have some sort of instant projectile

612
00:28:41,150 --> 00:28:43,771
on the plasma rifle, or at least much faster projectile.

613
00:28:44,672 --> 00:28:45,932
Which brings me to interlude number two.

614
00:28:47,512 --> 00:28:51,094
So every Christmas, I ask my grandma for a subscription

615
00:28:51,134 --> 00:28:51,794
to Edge Magazine.

616
00:28:53,374 --> 00:28:55,575
And every Christmas, I get a subscription

617
00:28:55,715 --> 00:28:56,476
to GamePro Magazine.

618
00:28:57,836 --> 00:28:58,296
Thank you, grandma.

619
00:29:00,997 --> 00:29:03,978
But lately, it's paid off because GamePro is actually

620
00:29:03,998 --> 00:29:04,998
turning into a very good magazine.

621
00:29:06,030 --> 00:29:10,233
And recently they had an article called The Psychology of Shooters.

622
00:29:12,195 --> 00:29:18,761
And in it they describe a study done by a pair of researchers named Andrew Przebilski

623
00:29:18,821 --> 00:29:23,765
and Scott Rigby where they modded Half-Life and they had one version where it was bloody

624
00:29:23,785 --> 00:29:27,709
and horrible and guts and violence and one version where it was non-violent.

625
00:29:27,729 --> 00:29:29,570
It was sort of like a game of tag.

626
00:29:30,772 --> 00:29:31,432
And what they found was...

627
00:29:31,741 --> 00:29:36,924
that both versions equally satisfy the basic needs that they were looking for, which were

628
00:29:37,004 --> 00:29:41,867
competence and autonomy. And you can read this either in GamePro or on Jamie Madigan's

629
00:29:41,907 --> 00:29:44,549
blog, psychologyofgames.com, which I heartily recommend.

630
00:29:47,310 --> 00:29:56,356
So their eventual sort of conclusion was that shooters satisfy human needs, and because

631
00:29:57,357 --> 00:30:01,459
both bloody shooter and tag shooter both satisfy competence and autonomy.

632
00:30:01,893 --> 00:30:03,774
They're both equally fun.

633
00:30:04,654 --> 00:30:06,915
But we all know that Tag of Duty would

634
00:30:06,955 --> 00:30:07,315
not sell.

635
00:30:09,736 --> 00:30:11,397
And I believe the reason is that our

636
00:30:11,437 --> 00:30:14,738
needs are much more complex than simple competence or

637
00:30:14,778 --> 00:30:15,138
autonomy.

638
00:30:16,319 --> 00:30:18,239
And I figure out everything with graphs, so

639
00:30:18,319 --> 00:30:18,720
let's make one.

640
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:24,582
Why is, is, let's see.

641
00:30:25,262 --> 00:30:27,503
So dodging is a competence, right.

642
00:30:28,023 --> 00:30:28,903
It's something you get good at.

643
00:30:29,845 --> 00:30:34,526
Why is it way more fun to dodge on normal than it is on legendary,

644
00:30:35,026 --> 00:30:37,567
when it kind of cheapens legendary if you can just dodge everything?

645
00:30:38,067 --> 00:30:39,727
And covering is always a choice,

646
00:30:39,747 --> 00:30:44,068
but why is it a more interesting choice on legendary when you really don't have any choice?

647
00:30:44,148 --> 00:30:45,169
You have to go take cover.

648
00:30:46,189 --> 00:30:51,430
And why is it more fun to dodge grunts and more fun to cover from elites?

649
00:30:51,890 --> 00:30:54,331
And why is it more fun to dodge if you're playing aggressively,

650
00:30:54,351 --> 00:30:57,532
and it's more fun to cover if you feel like you're wanting to play defensively?

651
00:30:59,356 --> 00:31:03,399
And my answer is that competence in a shooter,

652
00:31:04,540 --> 00:31:06,842
specifically dodging, is much more fun

653
00:31:06,862 --> 00:31:08,163
when you're under low pressure.

654
00:31:09,384 --> 00:31:11,165
And autonomy is much more fun when

655
00:31:11,185 --> 00:31:13,547
you're trying to tackle a problem that's

656
00:31:13,767 --> 00:31:14,548
much more difficult.

657
00:31:18,511 --> 00:31:21,133
So when games satisfy these complex needs,

658
00:31:21,514 --> 00:31:22,494
that's when they are really fun.

659
00:31:22,995 --> 00:31:25,857
And this complexity comes from the context

660
00:31:25,897 --> 00:31:27,518
that the needs are being satisfied in.

661
00:31:29,144 --> 00:31:31,926
Now, we already found out we can't control the context,

662
00:31:32,066 --> 00:31:33,467
because that's part of the audience.

663
00:31:34,128 --> 00:31:37,731
So what we have to do is match our fun activity to the context

664
00:31:37,771 --> 00:31:41,114
that those players are already experiencing.

665
00:31:44,957 --> 00:31:48,380
So for instance, context can make an activity feel natural

666
00:31:48,620 --> 00:31:51,002
when the activity flows out of the context.

667
00:31:51,443 --> 00:31:53,604
Some great examples of this, Assassin's Creed.

668
00:31:55,106 --> 00:31:56,707
There's no question in anybody's mind that this.

669
00:31:57,489 --> 00:32:02,632
is intending for them to sneak, and it feels the world really, really ingrains in you that

670
00:32:02,652 --> 00:32:06,275
you should be sneaking. I think the best example of the last year or so is Super Meat Boy.

671
00:32:06,535 --> 00:32:10,498
That poor guy is designed to die over and over and over and over again.

672
00:32:11,818 --> 00:32:16,722
But a context will also make an activity meaningful. I think this is what Clint Hocking was talking

673
00:32:16,742 --> 00:32:22,245
about in his talk yesterday. I'm still processing it, so I'm not exactly sure. Rescuing the

674
00:32:22,285 --> 00:32:26,308
princess for making it through a mission or becoming the Pokemon master.

675
00:32:28,854 --> 00:32:30,776
So what we did back in reality,

676
00:32:31,376 --> 00:32:33,518
where we split the plasma pistol and the plasma rifle bolts.

677
00:32:33,578 --> 00:32:35,759
So the plasma pistol became the slow, dodgeable version,

678
00:32:35,779 --> 00:32:37,901
the plasma rifle became the faster one that forced you to cover.

679
00:32:38,461 --> 00:32:41,404
And then on different difficulty levels, we sped up the projectile.

680
00:32:41,484 --> 00:32:44,786
So on normal, the plasma rifle's still dodgeable if you're far enough away,

681
00:32:45,246 --> 00:32:46,908
but on legendary, it's never dodgeable.

682
00:32:48,949 --> 00:32:51,491
And we changed the AI mechanics, again, split them.

683
00:32:52,432 --> 00:32:53,993
So the grunt kind of fights like your kid brother,

684
00:32:54,053 --> 00:32:56,255
like they shoot straight at you and they're really easy to confuse.

685
00:32:57,433 --> 00:32:59,615
If you hide, they come and look directly.

686
00:33:00,596 --> 00:33:02,497
Whereas the elites are a lot more cunning.

687
00:33:02,897 --> 00:33:03,698
They lead the player.

688
00:33:04,138 --> 00:33:06,900
And because they have a faster projectile, that's OK again.

689
00:33:07,640 --> 00:33:09,182
They track during the burst so that you

690
00:33:09,202 --> 00:33:11,823
have to consistently dodge the entire burst.

691
00:33:12,384 --> 00:33:17,607
And also, they suppress you before they come search.

692
00:33:17,687 --> 00:33:19,308
So what that means is if you take cover,

693
00:33:19,949 --> 00:33:21,970
they'll shoot at the cover and shoot around

694
00:33:22,010 --> 00:33:23,451
where they think you're going to be coming up.

695
00:33:23,711 --> 00:33:24,852
And they'll do that for a good 15, 20 seconds.

696
00:33:26,017 --> 00:33:28,038
before then coming up and very carefully,

697
00:33:28,659 --> 00:33:30,540
from usually as far away as they can,

698
00:33:30,600 --> 00:33:32,061
peeking around the cover to see if you're still there.

699
00:33:36,925 --> 00:33:38,406
We had two protagonists in Halo 2.

700
00:33:38,446 --> 00:33:40,768
There's the Chief, and we stopped displaying his health

701
00:33:40,928 --> 00:33:42,970
because what we wanted to do was make it so that

702
00:33:43,010 --> 00:33:45,692
as soon as your shields were down, you ran for cover.

703
00:33:46,232 --> 00:33:48,634
And you ran for cover with this feeling of,

704
00:33:48,774 --> 00:33:50,676
oh my goodness, this is really dangerous and scary.

705
00:33:51,757 --> 00:33:52,117
But then we...

706
00:33:52,655 --> 00:33:54,276
increased how fast the shield recharged,

707
00:33:54,296 --> 00:33:56,037
so you didn't have to stay in cover for very long.

708
00:33:56,437 --> 00:33:58,579
Because in Halo 1, you could just stand out of cover

709
00:33:58,599 --> 00:34:00,400
and dodge back and forth until your shields came back

710
00:34:00,740 --> 00:34:01,841
and you were shooting the whole time.

711
00:34:02,522 --> 00:34:04,163
It's a little bit more boring to stand behind a rock,

712
00:34:04,303 --> 00:34:05,824
so we wanted it to take less time.

713
00:34:06,244 --> 00:34:09,506
We even moved the shield meter right

714
00:34:09,546 --> 00:34:10,327
next to the motion tracker.

715
00:34:10,347 --> 00:34:11,508
So you could be crouching behind cover,

716
00:34:11,988 --> 00:34:13,569
looking at your shields and at the motion tracker

717
00:34:13,589 --> 00:34:15,350
to see if somebody was coming around the cover after you.

718
00:34:16,351 --> 00:34:19,293
For the Arbiter, we experimented with an invisibility,

719
00:34:19,393 --> 00:34:19,953
where he could.

720
00:34:20,303 --> 00:34:23,706
turn itself invisible for just long enough for his shields to almost start recharging,

721
00:34:25,367 --> 00:34:26,308
with more or less success.

722
00:34:28,650 --> 00:34:33,353
So I already mentioned that shots travel faster on Legendary, but we also changed how the

723
00:34:33,553 --> 00:34:34,654
weapon damage scale works.

724
00:34:34,714 --> 00:34:36,636
So first of all, it's per weapon now.

725
00:34:36,696 --> 00:34:40,979
It's no longer global on Halo 2, which meant that the Plasma Pistol we could make do a

726
00:34:41,039 --> 00:34:44,302
little bit more damage, but not really significantly, whereas the Plasma Rifle we could make do

727
00:34:44,322 --> 00:34:46,423
a lot more damage, but totally going to drive you into cover.

728
00:34:47,104 --> 00:34:50,086
Turns out this is a terrible way to balance difficulty, but I didn't know.

729
00:34:50,715 --> 00:34:51,256
that at the time.

730
00:34:53,357 --> 00:34:57,580
When we were calibrating, oh shoot, we didn't calibrate.

731
00:34:57,600 --> 00:34:58,781
Sorry about that, Halo 2.

732
00:34:59,422 --> 00:35:01,303
So almost at the end of the project,

733
00:35:01,323 --> 00:35:03,325
our AI counts got cut dramatically.

734
00:35:03,625 --> 00:35:06,127
We had to strip objects out like crazy.

735
00:35:06,747 --> 00:35:10,270
And we had very little time to recalibrate any of the weapons.

736
00:35:11,491 --> 00:35:14,253
So they ended up being about 15 world units per second.

737
00:35:14,273 --> 00:35:17,275
So slightly faster than Halo 1, and then

738
00:35:17,315 --> 00:35:18,496
a legendary much, much faster.

739
00:35:20,342 --> 00:35:24,143
So the normal experience of the player playing in Halo 2

740
00:35:24,223 --> 00:35:25,944
was that they can dodge grunts pretty easily

741
00:35:25,964 --> 00:35:27,485
and at least force them to cover.

742
00:35:27,545 --> 00:35:28,085
So far, so good.

743
00:35:28,966 --> 00:35:30,806
Unfortunately, because we had to remove so much cover,

744
00:35:32,247 --> 00:35:32,967
there wasn't enough.

