00:35:35,609 --> 00:35:36,829
that were supposed to drive you into cover,

747
00:35:36,929 --> 00:35:38,390
and there was maybe one piece of cover

748
00:35:38,530 --> 00:35:39,670
if we remembered to leave it in there.

749
00:35:40,331 --> 00:35:42,272
And because we had introduced Havoc in Halo 2,

750
00:35:42,972 --> 00:35:44,132
sometimes that cover would move.

751
00:35:44,212 --> 00:35:45,253
So they would throw a grenade at you,

752
00:35:45,353 --> 00:35:46,634
and your cover would go flying off the cliff,

753
00:35:46,654 --> 00:35:47,714
and then you'd be completely exposed.

754
00:35:49,238 --> 00:35:50,619
But that's not why it was totally broken.

755
00:35:51,219 --> 00:35:53,320
Why it was totally broken was because of the suppressing fire

756
00:35:53,340 --> 00:35:54,121
I talked about earlier.

757
00:35:54,141 --> 00:35:58,824
The AI would over-focus to a ridiculous degree.

758
00:35:59,124 --> 00:36:00,144
And I'll try to explain that.

759
00:36:00,705 --> 00:36:06,728
So basically, the way to always get the advantage of Halo 2

760
00:36:06,929 --> 00:36:09,650
is to take cover and then pop out at a different spot.

761
00:36:09,790 --> 00:36:12,732
So if the AI is shooting at you, you go behind cover.

762
00:36:14,153 --> 00:36:15,974
Then you pop out on the other side.

763
00:36:16,494 --> 00:36:18,296
And then you get two or three seconds to shoot at them

764
00:36:18,336 --> 00:36:18,916
before they shoot back.

765
00:36:19,528 --> 00:36:20,569
And then they start shooting at you,

766
00:36:20,609 --> 00:36:21,750
and you go back behind the cover,

767
00:36:21,770 --> 00:36:23,150
and you pop out on the first side.

768
00:36:23,571 --> 00:36:24,571
And it takes two or three seconds

769
00:36:24,771 --> 00:36:25,872
for them to figure out this tactic,

770
00:36:25,912 --> 00:36:27,613
and you can just do it over and over and over and over again.

771
00:36:28,073 --> 00:36:29,634
And if you ever played Legendary,

772
00:36:29,654 --> 00:36:30,635
you almost certainly figured this out,

773
00:36:30,655 --> 00:36:31,615
because it's the only way to get through.

774
00:36:31,635 --> 00:36:36,418
As far as multiplayer, the faster projectiles

775
00:36:36,458 --> 00:36:37,958
that the plasma rifle had were great,

776
00:36:38,019 --> 00:36:39,459
because they made the weapon useful at range,

777
00:36:39,779 --> 00:36:41,981
and we removed entirely the idea

778
00:36:42,001 --> 00:36:42,961
of movement sound from the game.

779
00:36:43,882 --> 00:36:46,403
Unfortunately, there was a bug that meant

780
00:36:46,443 --> 00:36:47,724
that if you were carrying an SMG,

781
00:36:47,764 --> 00:36:48,944
which was everywhere in Halo 2.

782
00:36:49,752 --> 00:36:52,592
And a plasma rifle, you were doing almost twice as much

783
00:36:52,652 --> 00:36:53,653
damage as anybody else.

784
00:36:53,873 --> 00:36:56,373
It was intended to reduce the amount of damage,

785
00:36:56,393 --> 00:36:58,034
but that wasn't fixed until the patch.

786
00:36:59,454 --> 00:37:01,495
And it was totally broken, because if you

787
00:37:01,535 --> 00:37:03,335
put two plasma rifles together, you

788
00:37:03,455 --> 00:37:05,696
could basically drop some of these shields almost

789
00:37:05,876 --> 00:37:06,616
instantaneously.

790
00:37:07,116 --> 00:37:08,257
And also, because the projectiles

791
00:37:08,277 --> 00:37:09,477
were moving faster for the player,

792
00:37:10,037 --> 00:37:12,478
the plasma pistol overcharge that we added,

793
00:37:12,498 --> 00:37:15,079
that's where they got the term noob combo.

794
00:37:18,920 --> 00:37:19,020
So.

795
00:37:19,877 --> 00:37:21,898
On Legendary, the experience is actually harder.

796
00:37:22,398 --> 00:37:25,200
It's not just more punishing.

797
00:37:25,620 --> 00:37:26,981
It's actually more difficult to dodge.

798
00:37:28,242 --> 00:37:30,063
Unfortunately, it is still more punishing,

799
00:37:30,563 --> 00:37:31,784
and especially on Marines.

800
00:37:32,024 --> 00:37:33,165
If you're playing Legendary on Halo 2,

801
00:37:33,345 --> 00:37:35,466
your Marines lifespan is about 10 seconds.

802
00:37:37,147 --> 00:37:39,629
And it was totally broken because we

803
00:37:39,649 --> 00:37:42,731
had engagement distances that were very far, which

804
00:37:42,751 --> 00:37:47,054
worked fine in Halo 1 because the AI would.

805
00:37:48,480 --> 00:37:52,882
close on you until its kind of slow projectiles were effective.

806
00:37:53,282 --> 00:37:55,643
But those projectiles were effective at a much farther distance.

807
00:37:55,663 --> 00:38:00,245
In fact, they were effective at a range beyond what even the player's weapons were effective

808
00:38:00,325 --> 00:38:00,405
at.

809
00:38:00,966 --> 00:38:05,568
And so when you get something like a jetpack elite wielding two plasma rifles, which we've

810
00:38:05,628 --> 00:38:10,470
already talked about is unbalanced in multiplayer, and then you add a 4X multiplayer on top of

811
00:38:10,490 --> 00:38:14,772
that and they're jumping around and they have recharging energy shields, you get a game

812
00:38:14,792 --> 00:38:17,753
that's really, really way too hard, especially my level.

813
00:38:19,853 --> 00:38:22,035
But luckily, we got to try it again.

814
00:38:22,055 --> 00:38:31,942
Our competition, as you can see, lots and lots of military games, and several of them

815
00:38:32,022 --> 00:38:33,103
feature cover systems.

816
00:38:35,905 --> 00:38:40,729
Now, our community at this point had been almost entirely single-player focused story

817
00:38:40,769 --> 00:38:42,110
guys, but with

818
00:38:42,493 --> 00:38:46,476
Halo 2 and Xbox Live, we started to get a much larger multiplayer community until they

819
00:38:46,596 --> 00:38:49,518
were given about roughly equal weight in Halo 3.

820
00:38:51,519 --> 00:38:58,723
And Halo became known for that kind of free-flowing combat that Halo 2 had got us, you know,

821
00:38:58,743 --> 00:39:00,324
dodging and sidestepping and covering.

822
00:39:01,345 --> 00:39:04,227
And so a cover system where you're sticking to cover just really didn't fit for us.

823
00:39:04,307 --> 00:39:08,950
We decided against, we figured our audience was established enough that we could sort

824
00:39:08,990 --> 00:39:12,192
of start ignoring the competition a little bit and going our own way.

825
00:39:14,010 --> 00:39:16,730
But again, the, the in-game context was the most important.

826
00:39:17,951 --> 00:39:19,311
There's no enemy elites in Halo 3.

827
00:39:20,031 --> 00:39:26,752
They switch sides on the Covenant, and so sometimes context is not outside of developer

828
00:39:26,772 --> 00:39:28,533
control, but it is outside of designer control.

829
00:39:30,593 --> 00:39:34,434
And that means there's no enemy plasma rifles, because the Brutes use the Spiker, and the

830
00:39:34,454 --> 00:39:39,475
Jackals use the Carbine, and Grunts use the Needler, and so nobody on the enemy side is

831
00:39:39,515 --> 00:39:40,375
using the plasma rifle.

832
00:39:41,776 --> 00:39:43,096
So does that mean my talk isn't over?

833
00:39:43,983 --> 00:39:45,783
No, it means an interlude.

834
00:39:47,504 --> 00:39:49,505
So pretty clearly, Halo 2 was a misstep.

835
00:39:50,525 --> 00:39:53,306
How much of a misstep is up for interpretation.

836
00:39:53,366 --> 00:39:56,507
But I spent a lot of time after Halo 2 ships.

837
00:39:56,927 --> 00:39:58,868
I went on a soul-searching journey

838
00:39:58,908 --> 00:40:01,308
to try to find out what should we have done?

839
00:40:01,408 --> 00:40:02,229
What would have been fun?

840
00:40:03,589 --> 00:40:05,570
I looked at lots of industry resources.

841
00:40:06,030 --> 00:40:08,050
Raph Koster says that games are edutainment.

842
00:40:08,931 --> 00:40:11,612
Will Wright says games are exploring a possibility space.

843
00:40:12,212 --> 00:40:13,572
Far be it for me to disagree with Will Wright.

844
00:40:14,679 --> 00:40:17,741
Sid Meier says games are a series of interesting choices.

845
00:40:18,621 --> 00:40:19,902
But when I looked at all these descriptions

846
00:40:19,942 --> 00:40:21,343
that designers were giving, they're

847
00:40:21,383 --> 00:40:22,684
describing their own games.

848
00:40:22,984 --> 00:40:24,044
Not really every game.

849
00:40:24,064 --> 00:40:25,565
It's certainly not Halo.

850
00:40:27,546 --> 00:40:28,747
So I looked into academia.

851
00:40:29,968 --> 00:40:31,569
I hope there's not too many academics in here.

852
00:40:31,609 --> 00:40:32,489
I may not make it out alive.

853
00:40:34,010 --> 00:40:36,471
I just picked one of their definitions at random.

854
00:40:36,551 --> 00:40:39,213
Games are an exercise of voluntary control systems.

855
00:40:39,617 --> 00:40:44,199
in which there is an opposition between forces confined by a procedure and rules in order

856
00:40:44,219 --> 00:40:46,420
to produce a disequilibrial outcome.

857
00:40:47,580 --> 00:40:47,740
Yeah.

858
00:40:48,300 --> 00:40:51,182
These guys aren't giving us a definition that is super useful.

859
00:40:51,222 --> 00:40:55,524
What they're doing is dissecting games into their various components, which is good for

860
00:40:55,984 --> 00:41:00,546
categorizing, not so good for building something that defies categories.

861
00:41:01,786 --> 00:41:03,387
I'm a philosopher by background.

862
00:41:03,407 --> 00:41:08,109
That's what my schooling is about, so I just kind of leave.

863
00:41:08,527 --> 00:41:11,809
through some of my old philosophy texts, Aristotle,

864
00:41:12,350 --> 00:41:17,534
talks a lot about catharsis and sort of how entertainment

865
00:41:17,594 --> 00:41:19,896
is about bringing yourself back into balance.

866
00:41:20,276 --> 00:41:20,876
That's interesting.

867
00:41:21,877 --> 00:41:23,639
Pascal says that games are a distraction

868
00:41:23,679 --> 00:41:24,579
from your imminent death.

869
00:41:27,362 --> 00:41:29,884
Wittgenstein says that games cannot be defined,

870
00:41:29,924 --> 00:41:31,605
which is not helpful, because then he says,

871
00:41:31,845 --> 00:41:32,986
because you already know what they are.

872
00:41:33,046 --> 00:41:34,567
And he's just trying to make a point about language.

873
00:41:34,587 --> 00:41:36,669
And so that doesn't help me at all.

874
00:41:38,422 --> 00:41:41,524
My final conclusion was that game designers should be philosophers.

875
00:41:41,564 --> 00:41:45,346
I think it actually helps you sit outside yourself and understand what you're thinking.

876
00:41:46,146 --> 00:41:47,667
But philosophers are not game designers.

877
00:41:49,749 --> 00:41:59,535
Csikszentmihalyi, in his book, Flow, says that flow, or some people could translate

878
00:41:59,575 --> 00:42:02,377
that into fun, is the immersion of the self in an activity.

879
00:42:02,417 --> 00:42:04,278
And he talks about the autotelic experience.

880
00:42:04,778 --> 00:42:05,659
And that basically means...

881
00:42:07,792 --> 00:42:10,893
What you're doing is completely pouring into yourself,

882
00:42:11,253 --> 00:42:13,835
and it has no purpose apart from yourself,

883
00:42:14,075 --> 00:42:18,137
even if it's accomplishing some other goal.

884
00:42:18,217 --> 00:42:20,738
Two other psychologists, Dessy and Ryan,

885
00:42:20,818 --> 00:42:23,079
talk a lot about self-determination theory,

886
00:42:23,279 --> 00:42:27,081
which is that human needs motivate people, which

887
00:42:27,141 --> 00:42:27,901
includes players.

888
00:42:28,902 --> 00:42:31,783
They focus a lot on intrinsic needs and extrinsic needs.

889
00:42:33,684 --> 00:42:35,245
I think their research is great, and I

890
00:42:35,305 --> 00:42:37,226
think Flo has a lot of great insights.

891
00:42:37,742 --> 00:42:39,702
But I sort of have a different take on the categories,

892
00:42:40,962 --> 00:42:43,603
which I will attempt to explain with a graph.

893
00:42:45,563 --> 00:42:51,885
So if you try to find a couple of orthogonal ways

894
00:42:51,905 --> 00:42:58,366
to classify needs, you'll find that some needs are need needs,

895
00:42:58,647 --> 00:43:01,107
meaning if you don't have them, you feel rotten.

896
00:43:02,507 --> 00:43:06,468
And some needs are want needs, where

897
00:43:06,954 --> 00:43:11,196
if you get them, it's a positive emotion, but if you don't have them, you're not sitting

898
00:43:11,236 --> 00:43:11,836
around miserable.

899
00:43:11,916 --> 00:43:16,477
And I decided to call those requirements for the need needs and aspirations, for those

900
00:43:16,537 --> 00:43:18,978
that are more positive but also optional.

901
00:43:20,179 --> 00:43:24,660
Now, clearly games are not, you're not going to die if you're not playing a game, so games

902
00:43:24,960 --> 00:43:27,921
probably provide aspirational needs of some kind.

903
00:43:32,183 --> 00:43:35,444
I also sort of played off of flow.

904
00:43:35,976 --> 00:43:38,957
and the idea of autotelic activities

905
00:43:39,497 --> 00:43:43,499
to come up with two new concepts of endotelic and exotelic.

906
00:43:43,559 --> 00:43:47,221
So telic is from telios, which means sort of like the goal

907
00:43:47,461 --> 00:43:47,961
or the end.

908
00:43:49,862 --> 00:43:51,482
Endo and exo meaning inner and outer.

909
00:43:52,203 --> 00:43:54,904
So basically, you have things that you

910
00:43:54,944 --> 00:44:00,146
do because you want a goal that comes from outside.

911
00:44:00,166 --> 00:44:02,507
So that's like cake, right?

912
00:44:03,247 --> 00:44:03,767
I want cake.

913
00:44:04,944 --> 00:44:09,328
it's going to end up inside of me. And I don't really care how it's provided. I don't really

914
00:44:09,348 --> 00:44:11,049
care if I made the cake, as long as it tastes good.

915
00:44:12,270 --> 00:44:20,397
Whereas Exotelic is actually I'm being used for something. So a lot of causes and religions

916
00:44:20,997 --> 00:44:27,523
are based on this. But much more humbly for games, it's just my skills are being used

917
00:44:27,543 --> 00:44:33,007
to make something happen. Which is why games need to be interactive, so that you can participate

918
00:44:33,087 --> 00:44:34,588
in them and cause something to happen.

919
00:44:35,505 --> 00:44:38,726
So I would put games into this upper right quadrant.

920
00:44:39,746 --> 00:44:42,307
And fun is the positive emotion that you get

921
00:44:42,387 --> 00:44:43,527
from meeting those needs.

922
00:44:50,589 --> 00:44:53,010
So if you think back to the graph,

923
00:44:53,490 --> 00:44:57,771
fun is that quadrant of meeting an exotelic aspiration.

924
00:44:58,712 --> 00:45:01,153
A game is a series of constraints

925
00:45:01,653 --> 00:45:04,093
on an activity that reliably and repeatedly.

926
00:45:05,023 --> 00:45:07,584
meet that exotelic aspiration for a specific audience.

927
00:45:09,105 --> 00:45:12,686
And I'm pretty sure that I just said that games are about fulfilling your dreams,

928
00:45:12,726 --> 00:45:14,247
so I'm going to go back to the red slide, sorry.

929
00:45:16,688 --> 00:45:20,010
So what exactly is the exotelic aspiration that a plasma rifle is intended to fulfill?

930
00:45:21,290 --> 00:45:24,652
Well, I think you have to describe these needs sort of

931
00:45:27,113 --> 00:45:31,134
poetically, they're not necessarily something reduced to a technical term, so

932
00:45:32,055 --> 00:45:34,576
the first one is I think they make the player feel like they're on another level.

933
00:45:35,087 --> 00:45:41,809
They're making their enemies look dumb, and running rings around them is a good sort of

934
00:45:41,850 --> 00:45:42,090
trope.

935
00:45:43,150 --> 00:45:46,431
You want to manipulate your enemies and frighten them and play with them before you kill them.

936
00:45:47,892 --> 00:45:52,413
I think the plasma rifle also fulfills the aspiration to be cool under fire.

937
00:45:52,973 --> 00:45:57,655
You're facing danger, and it's real danger, but you approach it with like kind of a discipline

938
00:45:57,715 --> 00:46:01,856
and you don't panic and you do things just the right way and you end up winning.

939
00:46:03,497 --> 00:46:03,837
And also...

940
00:46:04,892 --> 00:46:06,852
the plasma rifle is all about turning the tables.

941
00:46:07,353 --> 00:46:10,474
So the enemy's trying to use the plasma rifle on you,

942
00:46:10,794 --> 00:46:11,834
and you take it from them, and you

943
00:46:11,935 --> 00:46:14,255
use it on them and their friends much more effectively

944
00:46:14,295 --> 00:46:14,816
than they could.

945
00:46:17,197 --> 00:46:20,458
Turns out, this is not just about the plasma rifle.

946
00:46:20,598 --> 00:46:21,979
This is about every enemy weapon.

947
00:46:22,039 --> 00:46:23,759
So even though Halo 3 doesn't really

948
00:46:23,779 --> 00:46:26,841
feature the plasma rifle, the legacy of the plasma rifle

949
00:46:27,301 --> 00:46:29,342
goes through to all the other enemy weapons in the game.

950
00:46:30,862 --> 00:46:33,463
So for almost every weapon.

951
00:46:33,964 --> 00:46:35,985
that the enemy uses in Halo 3.

952
00:46:36,945 --> 00:46:37,806
It's slower for enemies.

953
00:46:39,526 --> 00:46:42,127
Basically, they start out a little bit slow,

954
00:46:42,167 --> 00:46:44,608
and then they accelerate, which gives you plenty of time

955
00:46:44,668 --> 00:46:46,169
to see where it's coming and then dodge it.

956
00:46:46,849 --> 00:46:49,710
They also have ramp up time, so the rate of fire

957
00:46:49,750 --> 00:46:51,591
actually increases the longer you hold on the trigger.

958
00:46:53,631 --> 00:46:55,032
But it's much faster for players.

959
00:46:55,072 --> 00:46:57,393
So the player in Halo 3 always uses the speed

960
00:46:57,433 --> 00:46:58,853
that the AI would have on Legendary,

961
00:46:59,113 --> 00:47:00,314
and that includes multiplayer.

962
00:47:03,127 --> 00:47:05,729
When you're firing a weapon, you don't, as a player,

963
00:47:05,889 --> 00:47:07,690
care very much that it starts out slow,

964
00:47:07,790 --> 00:47:10,131
as long as it gets to a quick speed very fast,

965
00:47:10,171 --> 00:47:11,632
so you have the range that you need.

966
00:47:12,092 --> 00:47:14,834
And players don't burst fire, at least not in the short bursts

967
00:47:14,874 --> 00:47:16,695
that the AI does, so the ramp up isn't

968
00:47:16,775 --> 00:47:17,856
as much of a factor for them.

969
00:47:19,537 --> 00:47:21,458
This means that the player can always turn the tables

970
00:47:21,998 --> 00:47:23,559
on the enemy by picking up their weapon

971
00:47:23,579 --> 00:47:24,339
and using it against them.

972
00:47:25,400 --> 00:47:28,322
The AI for grunts is comically incompetent.

973
00:47:28,362 --> 00:47:31,003
They're always running away and panicking and putting

974
00:47:31,043 --> 00:47:31,764
their arms up in the air.

975
00:47:33,634 --> 00:47:35,515
We made sure that you could kill them with a single melee attack,

976
00:47:35,535 --> 00:47:37,777
so you can kind of jump down amongst them like a cat

977
00:47:37,837 --> 00:47:39,278
amongst mice and just start swinging.

978
00:47:40,138 --> 00:47:42,900
But the elites, on the other hand, are dangerous,

979
00:47:42,960 --> 00:47:44,581
but it's a manageable danger.

980
00:47:45,982 --> 00:47:49,804
We added an idea in the AI of out-of-cover firing.

981
00:47:50,404 --> 00:47:52,926
So when you first emerge from cover,

982
00:47:52,946 --> 00:47:55,508
they're going to take a little while to start shooting at you.

983
00:47:55,528 --> 00:47:58,990
They're going to shoot at you in shorter bursts

984
00:47:59,110 --> 00:48:00,471
with longer durations between them.

985
00:48:00,771 --> 00:48:01,872
But the longer you stay out of cover,

986
00:48:02,346 --> 00:48:03,387
they're gonna start honing in on you,

987
00:48:03,407 --> 00:48:04,327
they're gonna be more accurate,

988
00:48:04,347 --> 00:48:05,448
they're gonna shoot more often,

989
00:48:05,468 --> 00:48:08,050
they're gonna shoot with less time in between shots.

990
00:48:08,770 --> 00:48:11,792
And so, what this meant was that

991
00:48:13,213 --> 00:48:14,614
for a while you could stay out of cover,

992
00:48:15,975 --> 00:48:17,976
but after a while, without you even noticing it,

993
00:48:18,076 --> 00:48:19,337
because you probably were habituated,

994
00:48:20,978 --> 00:48:22,899
the AI would just suddenly be able to start hitting you

995
00:48:22,919 --> 00:48:24,040
and that would drive you back into cover.

996
00:48:25,581 --> 00:48:27,122
We reduced the damage scale on Legendary,

997
00:48:27,182 --> 00:48:29,643
that global damage scale that was so high before.

998
00:48:30,365 --> 00:48:33,927
because we just decided that damage is not the right way to make a game harder.

999
00:48:35,068 --> 00:48:37,189
I believe that the right way to make a game harder is to make it faster.

1000
00:48:37,709 --> 00:48:42,892
So, the same experience slowed down becomes easy.

1001
00:48:43,913 --> 00:48:45,634
The same experience sped up becomes harder.

1002
00:48:45,654 --> 00:48:49,596
The projectiles go faster, the AI fire delays get shorter,

1003
00:48:49,616 --> 00:48:53,778
in fact the entire combat cycle gets faster, so it's probably like 22 seconds of fun or something like that.

1004
00:48:55,691 --> 00:48:59,972
And this emerged in a concept we call reciprocal difficulty.

1005
00:49:00,212 --> 00:49:02,773
So basically, it's a form of dynamic difficulty,

1006
00:49:02,793 --> 00:49:06,794
but it's not handled by the computer or the AI.

1007
00:49:06,814 --> 00:49:07,815
It's actually driven by the player.

1008
00:49:08,235 --> 00:49:10,576
So the more you push a Halo encounter,

1009
00:49:10,616 --> 00:49:14,117
the more it pushes back, which rewards risk.

1010
00:49:14,237 --> 00:49:15,837
Because if you push really hard, you

1011
00:49:15,857 --> 00:49:17,818
can break through very fast, as long

1012
00:49:17,858 --> 00:49:19,858
as you can handle how hard it's pushing back at you.

1013
00:49:20,159 --> 00:49:21,579
But at the same time, it forgives failure.

1014
00:49:21,679 --> 00:49:23,720
So as soon as you withdraw, it withdraws.

1015
00:49:24,243 --> 00:49:26,785
You'll notice in Halo, the AI don't really chase you very much.

1016
00:49:27,985 --> 00:49:32,167
And we don't punish you at all for risking and then failing and running away.

1017
00:49:32,207 --> 00:49:33,728
Your shields come back, your health comes back.

1018
00:49:34,308 --> 00:49:36,029
The AI resets, basically.

1019
00:49:40,491 --> 00:49:44,753
So I recently read a really fascinating book called Sleights of Mind, and it's a couple

1020
00:49:44,794 --> 00:49:48,335
of neuroscientists who go into the world of magic, and they try to learn everything they

1021
00:49:48,355 --> 00:49:50,957
can from the techniques that the magicians have.

1022
00:49:52,633 --> 00:49:55,796
to figure out what's going on inside of the brain of the people that they're fooling.

1023
00:49:56,516 --> 00:50:02,660
And one of the things that they talk about in the context of a pickpocket is that you

1024
00:50:02,700 --> 00:50:03,721
have a spotlight of attention.

1025
00:50:04,081 --> 00:50:09,225
And anytime you attend to one thing, you are ignoring virtually everything else that is

1026
00:50:09,265 --> 00:50:10,446
not happening in your spotlight.

1027
00:50:10,486 --> 00:50:12,847
So that's the tunnel vision that we describe.

1028
00:50:13,208 --> 00:50:15,449
And magicians exploit this feature mercilessly.

1029
00:50:15,509 --> 00:50:18,711
The doves fly up, and you all look up, as most of you probably looked up just because

1030
00:50:18,731 --> 00:50:19,292
they went like that.

1031
00:50:19,352 --> 00:50:20,773
And then over here, they're doing something else.

1032
00:50:21,743 --> 00:50:23,303
And I figured, you know, if magicians can do that,

1033
00:50:23,763 --> 00:50:26,464
if they can use distraction, then a game designer

1034
00:50:26,484 --> 00:50:28,204
should be able to do the opposite in order

1035
00:50:28,244 --> 00:50:29,985
to kind of hyper-focus while they're calibrating.

1036
00:50:30,945 --> 00:50:32,706
So just a random smattering ideas

1037
00:50:32,746 --> 00:50:33,626
on how to focus your attention.

1038
00:50:33,646 --> 00:50:36,747
I always create custom test spaces

1039
00:50:36,827 --> 00:50:38,627
so that nothing else is going on except for the thing

1040
00:50:38,647 --> 00:50:39,827
that I'm trying to calibrate.

1041
00:50:40,528 --> 00:50:42,608
You obviously can't ship a game that way,

1042
00:50:42,648 --> 00:50:44,168
because eventually you need to try it all together.

1043
00:50:44,269 --> 00:50:46,809
But I found that it helps you focus and not

1044
00:50:46,829 --> 00:50:48,490
get distracted on the other things that are broken.

1045
00:50:50,548 --> 00:50:52,609
if they're too fun, get distracted just playing the game.

1046
00:50:54,429 --> 00:50:56,910
I use post-it notes, so if I'm balancing the plasma rifle,

1047
00:50:56,950 --> 00:50:59,631
I'll put a post-it note that says plasma rifle on the screen.

1048
00:50:59,671 --> 00:51:00,971
Right now I have one that says talk faster.

1049
00:51:04,092 --> 00:51:08,593
I stare at Rorschach tests and try not to see pictures.

1050
00:51:09,193 --> 00:51:11,693
I don't know, this is like the equivalent of last year's mouth

1051
00:51:11,753 --> 00:51:12,754
noises with the warthog.

1052
00:51:12,794 --> 00:51:18,075
But I feel like if you can train your brain to go into a state

1053
00:51:18,095 --> 00:51:19,375
where it's not looking for patterns,

1054
00:51:19,535 --> 00:51:20,255
you'll be able to see.

1055
00:51:21,581 --> 00:51:25,825
specific patterns and put your spotlight directly on them more effectively.

1056
00:51:27,707 --> 00:51:29,089
You need to avoid habituation.

1057
00:51:30,510 --> 00:51:32,512
The way I do that is I take periodic breaks.

1058
00:51:32,933 --> 00:51:35,836
Again, the custom test spaces are great for that because you play through it, and then

1059
00:51:35,856 --> 00:51:37,037
when you get to the end, you just take a break.

1060
00:51:37,497 --> 00:51:39,579
Or maybe you try tweaking something else.

1061
00:51:41,481 --> 00:51:42,823
Sometimes I'll intentionally break something.

1062
00:51:42,843 --> 00:51:44,705
I usually don't check this in, but I'll just...

1063
00:51:45,220 --> 00:51:48,483
I'll just break something and play the game with a broken plasma rifle for a while, so

1064
00:51:48,543 --> 00:51:53,006
I habituate to something else, and then when I put it back, I'm more sensitive to it.

1065
00:51:54,347 --> 00:51:57,749
And I also do total recalibrations, and this drives producers nuts.

1066
00:51:58,250 --> 00:52:04,574
But I'll basically save off a copy, blank out everything, and try to retune it from

1067
00:52:04,634 --> 00:52:04,974
scratch.

1068
00:52:05,235 --> 00:52:08,097
And then I'll compare the two, and I'll say, oh, these are really close.

1069
00:52:08,337 --> 00:52:10,458
I bet you that's, you know, right.

1070
00:52:11,059 --> 00:52:12,200
Or hey, these are totally different.

1071
00:52:12,220 --> 00:52:13,901
And then I kind of have two things to compare.

1072
00:52:14,434 --> 00:52:15,555
people can tell me which one they like more.

1073
00:52:17,576 --> 00:52:19,697
So at the end of all that, in Halo 3,

1074
00:52:19,997 --> 00:52:22,938
14 world units per second, about 75% faster

1075
00:52:22,978 --> 00:52:24,179
on Legendary and in multiplayer.

1076
00:52:25,679 --> 00:52:28,741
The normal experience was that even on Legendary,

1077
00:52:28,761 --> 00:52:30,562
you can dodge for short amounts of time,

1078
00:52:31,002 --> 00:52:33,123
but eventually you have to return into cover.

1079
00:52:34,203 --> 00:52:35,864
The unintended consequences of this

1080
00:52:35,924 --> 00:52:40,466
was that we started to see players sort of standardizing

1081
00:52:40,506 --> 00:52:41,046
how they were playing.

1082
00:52:41,744 --> 00:52:44,587
even on normal or on legendary, different quality of players,

1083
00:52:44,907 --> 00:52:46,448
they would kind of have the same pattern.

1084
00:52:46,508 --> 00:52:49,731
And we would see that a level was

1085
00:52:49,771 --> 00:52:51,933
taking about the same time for everybody to complete.

1086
00:52:55,035 --> 00:52:57,818
And it wasn't badly broken, which was a good thing.

1087
00:52:59,239 --> 00:53:02,822
In multiplayer, people started to use the plasma rifle

1088
00:53:02,842 --> 00:53:06,145
more often because it was faster and it was more effective,

1089
00:53:06,765 --> 00:53:08,587
especially when combining arms with teammates.

1090
00:53:10,657 --> 00:53:13,259
We saw people want to use the alien weapons more,

1091
00:53:13,319 --> 00:53:16,682
and they want to play as elites more, which was useful later on.

1092
00:53:16,802 --> 00:53:17,883
And again, not badly broken.

1093
00:53:18,924 --> 00:53:21,145
The legendary experience, legendary is very hard.

1094
00:53:21,165 --> 00:53:21,726
It's supposed to be.

1095
00:53:22,226 --> 00:53:23,767
But it's not punishing hard.

1096
00:53:23,948 --> 00:53:26,289
It just requires a very high level of skill.

1097
00:53:28,371 --> 00:53:31,173
And so we saw people, especially reviewers,

1098
00:53:31,213 --> 00:53:32,634
that were playing on higher difficulty levels

1099
00:53:32,654 --> 00:53:33,695
were giving it a higher score.

1100
00:53:33,815 --> 00:53:36,397
And we also developed this bizarre sub-community.

1101
00:53:36,778 --> 00:53:39,819
where they play solo legendary all skulls on it.

1102
00:53:39,859 --> 00:53:40,919
You know what the skulls are.

1103
00:53:40,979 --> 00:53:42,760
I mean, that makes it incredibly hard.

1104
00:53:43,060 --> 00:53:44,521
But at the same time, it's still doable

1105
00:53:44,561 --> 00:53:47,882
because we're not cranking up the damage

1106
00:53:47,902 --> 00:53:48,762
to ridiculous levels.

1107
00:53:49,903 --> 00:53:51,383
So hopefully not badly broken.

1108
00:53:52,163 --> 00:53:56,505
Which brings me to ODST, which was named Halo 3 ODST

1109
00:53:56,525 --> 00:53:59,586
for a reason, because the sandbox didn't really change.

1110
00:54:00,546 --> 00:54:04,768
Which brings me to Halo Reach, where the plasma rifle was

1111
00:54:04,828 --> 00:54:06,488
reborn as the plasma.

1112
00:54:08,428 --> 00:54:12,089
So our competition was pretty clear.

1113
00:54:14,470 --> 00:54:17,132
We, by that time, had a large collection of sub-communities.

1114
00:54:17,172 --> 00:54:18,592
So there's the multiplayer-only community.

1115
00:54:18,652 --> 00:54:21,413
There's the people that just wanted to jump into Forge.

1116
00:54:22,054 --> 00:54:23,154
Firefight was really popular.

1117
00:54:24,315 --> 00:54:27,996
And one of the sub-communities was Halo developers.

1118
00:54:28,796 --> 00:54:31,558
Basically, almost every member of the original team

1119
00:54:31,578 --> 00:54:33,638
had already moved on to the next big thing by then.

1120
00:54:34,219 --> 00:54:37,940
And fully half of the Reach team was hired after Halo 3 shipped.

1121
00:54:40,400 --> 00:54:45,644
So that meant, to some extent, Halo Reach was made by the community, for the community,

1122
00:54:45,824 --> 00:54:47,686
and they were very in tune with what the community wanted.

1123
00:54:50,148 --> 00:54:54,692
Which brought up things like Elites versus Spartans, where they wanted total weapon parity

1124
00:54:54,752 --> 00:55:00,277
between the Elite weapons and the Spartan weapons, which meant that they needed an Elite

1125
00:55:01,278 --> 00:55:04,360
assault rifle, which is what the Platinum Repeater eventually became.

1126
00:55:05,490 --> 00:55:09,474
and that meant basically all they wanted for that game was the instant projectiles

1127
00:55:09,514 --> 00:55:10,955
because otherwise it just wasn't fair.

1128
00:55:10,995 --> 00:55:14,458
It's hard to hit a human with a dodgeable projectile.

1129
00:55:15,339 --> 00:55:18,122
And they really were intent on going back to the feel of Halo 1,

1130
00:55:18,182 --> 00:55:20,504
back to fighting elites, they removed dual wielding,

1131
00:55:21,144 --> 00:55:22,626
there are lots more plasma rifles in the game.

1132
00:55:24,547 --> 00:55:26,929
So according to the Halo re-strategy guide,

1133
00:55:26,949 --> 00:55:29,952
did I mention I didn't really work on this game?

1134
00:55:30,363 --> 00:55:31,724
The plasma rifle's primary purpose

1135
00:55:31,784 --> 00:55:34,566
is to disable the shields of close, you know, forget it.

1136
00:55:34,586 --> 00:55:38,089
I'm going to take a lesson from the plasma rifle.

1137
00:55:38,109 --> 00:55:39,150
I'm going to kind of dodge this one.

1138
00:55:39,550 --> 00:55:41,651
It's not fair for an ex-Bungie designer

1139
00:55:41,671 --> 00:55:44,573
to talk about the decisions that the current design team made.

1140
00:55:45,134 --> 00:55:46,815
And I'm almost out of time anyway.

1141
00:55:50,257 --> 00:55:53,920
But you find that in the middle of the project,

1142
00:55:54,260 --> 00:55:55,761
things were very different than Halo 3.

1143
00:55:55,861 --> 00:55:57,202
But by the end of the project, they had sort of

1144
00:55:57,572 --> 00:56:00,534
veered back in the direction of what we had at the end of Halo 3.

1145
00:56:02,395 --> 00:56:03,095
So conclusions.

1146
00:56:05,396 --> 00:56:06,497
Tuning and balancing are not the same.

1147
00:56:06,717 --> 00:56:12,340
Balance is about longevity, especially in multiplayer, and tuning is really the craft

1148
00:56:12,500 --> 00:56:22,346
of making something fun, which is, depending on which theory section you agreed with, specialized

1149
00:56:22,426 --> 00:56:26,448
brain circuit activity, or performing a skill in a natural, meaningful context.

1150
00:56:26,958 --> 00:56:28,619
or meeting exotelic aspiration.

1151
00:56:29,739 --> 00:56:32,380
The tuning process, first you understand your audience,

1152
00:56:32,420 --> 00:56:34,401
either by choosing it or inheriting it,

1153
00:56:35,161 --> 00:56:37,162
because your audience is inseparable

1154
00:56:37,222 --> 00:56:38,103
from their context.

1155
00:56:38,543 --> 00:56:41,484
Then you find their exotelic aspiration, or the activity

1156
00:56:41,504 --> 00:56:42,024
that they want to do.

1157
00:56:44,545 --> 00:56:47,727
You choose a fun activity that is reactive, repeatable,

1158
00:56:47,927 --> 00:56:48,387
reliable.

1159
00:56:48,847 --> 00:56:50,048
And keep in mind, these are rare,

1160
00:56:50,268 --> 00:56:53,269
and that's why you're going to very rarely invent

1161
00:56:53,289 --> 00:56:54,510
an entirely new kind of game.

1162
00:56:55,329 --> 00:56:58,130
Then you integrate the mechanics so that they support each other

1163
00:56:58,150 --> 00:57:03,293
and calibrate the values to your internal player model,

1164
00:57:04,013 --> 00:57:05,734
sometimes starting over from scratch.

1165
00:57:07,014 --> 00:57:08,975
And then verify the experience through user research,

1166
00:57:09,035 --> 00:57:10,556
and hopefully nothing is badly broken.

1167
